UNDIAGNOSED ILLNESS - CHINA: (GUANGXI ZHUANG AUTONOMOUS REGION), REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
****************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: 7 Nov 2014
Source: Daily Star [edited]
http://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/409171/Agony-villagers-deformed-mystery-disease


A mystery disease is turning a rural village into a community of mutants crippled and deformed by a painful condition. It has left health experts baffled as villagers complain of their hands and feet slowly twisting out of shape.

It has affected mostly men, but all are suffering as the bones in their limbs slowly deform, and, in many cases, painful pustules are also appearing on their skin.

Medics are now desperately trying to help villagers in Yalong township, on the outskirts of the city of Hechi in southern China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.

Health care worker Doctor Li Wu, 41, said: "In many cases, this doesn't only just look bad, it also significantly affects the person's ability to work. For people in a rural community who have to carry out a lot of manual work, it is a disaster."

More than 20 villagers have the bizarre condition and in many cases have been suffering from it for years.

One victim, 38, can only do light work around the house now after 1st discovering she was suffering from the problem 12 years ago. She said: "Many of my neighbours have been to different health centres and hospitals, but nobody seems to know what the problem is, although it's great that the experts have now come here to try and get to the bottom of it."

They have been carrying out tests on the water and on the food that the villagers have been growing in the mountainous region.

The current most popular theory is that they are all suffering from a variation of Kaschin-Beck disease [also known as KBD], a bone infection which principally is caused by lack of selenium in water or food, which in turn leads to a susceptibility to the condition.

Although toxic in large amounts, a small amount of selenium is vital in animals, including humans, for a healthy, functioning body.

Experts say it is too early to say, although they are hoping that they will be able to prevent further outbreaks and also offer some alleviation to those already infected.

[Byline: Paul Mosley]

