Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Kashin-Beck disease (KBD) is a devastating bone disease without a cure. It most often affects children and affects the growth plates resulting people of short stature. It is an endemic osteochondropathy, or bone disease occurring most often in China, Tibet, North Korea and some parts of Siberia.

While a number of things have been possibly linked as a possible cause, a positive cause and treatment remain elusive. Selenium deficiency was at one time linked to this disease. Addition of selenium to the diet in some regions may help prevent the disease but it does not reverse the situation or treat an existing situation. In other regions where the disease has occurred selenium has had little to no effect in preventing KBD. Selenium in doses that are too high can be toxic to the individual, creating other difficulties. Likewise, treatment with iodine (often insufficient in the diet) has shown some benefit for treatment.

KBD has also been linked to a variety of mycotoxins, including _Fusarium_ sp. and _Alternaria_ sp. There are a number of others may be possible causes as well. It could also be a combination of these mycotoxins.

There are excellent, yet sad and heart breaking photos of the affected individuals on the original website. The difference in KBD and what is happening to these people is that most of them seem to be adults, where as KBD most commonly affects growing individuals, having a profound effect on the growth plates. Furthermore, I could not find a reference regarding KBD that point to pustules to accompany the bone deformities.

While this disease may indeed be a mycotoxin or combination of mycotoxins in the grain based food stuffs, it strikes me that it looks a bit like a parasite invasion. This article tells us that doctors are testing food and water, but it does not tell us if any cultures of pustules have been done. It does not tell us if individuals have been taken to medical facilities for bone scans or culture or any other testing. It only says that some have traveled to medical facilities.

If someone has more information on this as yet undiagnosed disease, what has been tested for and results, we would appreciate your communication.

China, Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region is located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at
http://healthmap.org/r/awG8. - Mod.TG

